{"source_key":"sha256-852da461b9759bc2736926d9891eb9a3","record_index":10032,"record_hash":"sha256:ea6a853d63457408b929399d9422d78ccefb602bcaeafcc6198cdd565bb8ae45","timestamp":"2026-05-20T18:45:18.458Z","kind":"tool_result","source_event_kind":"codex:response_item:function_call_output","role":null,"text":"{\"status\":{\"[REDACTED:entropy]\":{\"completed\":\"Use pattern:\\n\\n1. `sessions branch <branch> --limit 5`\\n2. `timeline <session> --limit 20`\\n3. For the giant backfill turn, start with `records <session> --turn <turn> --from end --limit 100`\\n4. Walk backward only if the tail says “continued from above” or lacks the branch-relevant conclusion.\\n\\n`--from start|end|<index>` is almost sufficient, but it’s missing one small thing: **reverse paging**.\\n\\nFor a huge late-captured transcript, the useful stuff is usually near the end: final state, decisions, files touched, blockers, next steps. Starting at `end` is right, but after reading the last 100 records I need a clean way to request “the previous 100 before this chunk.” An index can do it if records expose stable indexes, but it’s clunky unless the response includes cursors/index boundaries.\\n\\nMinimal recommendation:\\n\\n```sh\\nbut agentlog records <session-key> --turn <turn-key> --from end --limit 100\\n```\\n\\nResponse should include:\\n\\n```text\\nshowing records 4900..4999 of 5000\\nprevious-from=4800\\nnext-from=end\\n```\\n\\nThen I can page:\\n\\n```sh\\nbut agentlog records <session-key> --turn <turn-key> --from 4800 --limit 100\\n```\\n\\nI would **not** add filtering yet. Record filtering/search/previews/ranges are tempting, but they turn a minimal catch-up tool into a mini log database. For this scenario, the best minimal add is **turn metadata plus reverse-friendly pagination**.\\n\\nI’d want `timeline` to flag the giant backfill clearly:\\n\\n```text\\nturn abc123  5,000 records  backfilled  2026-05-20  touched: crates/..., apps/...\\n```\\n\\nIf you add exactly one “preview” feature, make it automatic in `timeline`: show a short synthesized/recorded turn summary if one exists, not a new command. But don’t block the minimal toolset on summaries.\\n\\nSo: keep the three tools, make record indexes stable, include total/count/window boundaries, and make `--from end` practically pageable backward. That’s enough.\"},\"019e46b4-7d65-7003-a\n[TRUNCATED]\ng sessions branch foo --interesting\\n```\\n\\nHide obvious noise: tiny sessions, no user input, no changes, failed startup, pure browsing unless linked to a decision.\\n\\n```sh\\nbut agentlog sessions branch foo --files crates/foo apps/bar\\n```\\n\\nFind sessions relevant to files I’m about to touch.\\n\\n```sh\\nbut agentlog timeline <session> --summary\\n```\\n\\nGive turn-level summaries, not raw transcript shape.\\n\\nTimeline needs these per turn:\\n\\n- `turn_key`\\n- timestamp\\n- user request summary\\n- assistant action summary\\n- tools used\\n- files touched\\n- tests run/result\\n- commits/staged changes\\n- errors/blockers\\n- spawned sessions\\n- linked review comments\\n- compaction/resume links\\n- “importance” or “decision” marker\\n\\nRecords needs better slicing affordances:\\n\\n```sh\\nbut agentlog records <session> --around-turn <turn> --context 3\\nbut agentlog records <session> --kind user|assistant|tool|error|decision\\nbut agentlog records <session> --grep \\\"panic\\\"\\nbut agentlog records <session> --files crates/foo/src/lib.rs\\n```\\n\\n`--from start|end|<index>` is too primitive. On a messy branch I rarely know the index. I know the file, error, commit, review comment, or approximate event.\\n\\nThe biggest missing concept is **lineage**. If there are compaction/resume sessions, I need the tool to say:\\n\\n> this session continues session A, which compacted session B; subagents C and D were spawned from turn T; review session E commented on commit X.\\n\\nSo I’d probably reshape the minimal set like this:\\n\\n1. `but agentlog sessions ... --tree --interesting`\\n2. `but agentlog timeline <session-key> [--summary] [--with-children]`\\n3. `but agentlog records <session-key> --turn <turn-key> [--around N | --kind K | --grep Q]`\\n\\nVerdict: **good skeleton, not enough for receiving-agent catch-up**. Add session classification, parent/root lineage, summaries, touched files/commits/tests, and filtering. Otherwise the agent burns time spelunking sidecar sessions instead of understanding the branch.\"}},\"timed_out\":false}","tool_name":null,"tool_input":null,"source_record":{"timestamp":"2026-05-20T18:45:18.458Z","type":"response_item","payload":{"type":"function_call_output","call_id":"[REDACTED:entropy]"}}}